EDITORIAL

  Steel City sports teams  
bringing back glory days

Perhaps this decade the moniker
“City of Champions” will retum' to
Pittsburgh.

On Dec. 20, the Pitt _football team
beat the North Carolina State Wolfpack
34-19 in the Visit Florida Tangerine
Bowl. This marks the first bowl victory
for Pitt since the 1989 John Hancock
Bowl. It’s also head coach Walt Harris’
first bowl victory.

Congratulations to the Panthers on a
phenomenal performance.

And more importantly, Pitt fans
showed up in droves to cheer the team to
victory. We should all be proud that so
many made the trek, especially since the
journey from Pittsburgh to Orlando, Fla,
is much longer than the one from North
Carolina. -

Even better, those who showed up
went wild. Unlike games at Heinz Field,
where at some moments the silence is
deafening, the Pitt section kept the vol-
ume cranked the entire time. The fans
showed the enthusiasm that should be
normal for every game.

Although the Tangerine Bowl is con-
sidered a less-prestigious bowl, that did
not seem to matter to the fans and the
team. Following the victory, Pitt fans
waited in the lobby of the hotel for the
team to return and congratulated them.
While other schools scoff at any non-

. Bowl Championship Series game, Pitt

was clearly happy to be there — as we
should be. A bowl game is a bowl game,
and by playing in it the program received
a big boost. As the ESPN commentators
noted during the game, this should great-
ly help recruiting. Games such as the
Tangerine Bowl should remain in place.
But the football team is not the only
team that brought pride to Pitt. After a
victory over Boston College on Saturday,
the men’s basketball team broke into the
top 25 for the ﬁrst time since 1998. We

would like to congratulate them as well,‘
and we look forward to even greater.

accomplishments. .
, And Pitt’s teams are not the only ones
allowing Pittsburghers to hold their heads
high. In two weeks, the Steelers will host
a playoff game at ‘Heinz Field after ﬁnish-
ing with the best record in the AFC and
snapping a streak of three playoff-less
years. Many sports commentators predict
the Steelers will reach the Super Bowl, to
be played in New Orleans on Feb. 3.
Let’s hope their predictions come
true. After all, the only city better for a
bowl game than Orlando — whether it is

a college bowl or the Super Bowl — is-

New Orleans. Pittsburgh sports are once
again giving us reason to be proud. To
quote Pitt football wide receiver Antonio
Bryant, “let’s keep the party going.”_

