Following the huge success of Rockstar Games’
“Grand Theft Auto_3,” the game company released its
second high-speed title, “Smuggler’s Run 2.”

In the company’s_ second
“Smuggler’s Run” effort, “Smuggler’s
Run 2” fails, to bring the well—rounded
assortment of graphics, strong plot and
exciting game play that its predecessor
displayed.

The off-road racing game, which is the self—pro—
claimed “ultimate off-road driving adventure,” has the
game player working for smugglers by delivering an
array of contraband while escaping authorities and
rivals.

“Grand Theft Auto 3,” which is one of this year’s
hottest games, is so successful because game players
really have to outthink their foes on each mission. The
plot grows throughout the game because you are con-
stantly working for new corrupt entities. By contrast,

Zap

“Smuggler’s Run 2” just doesn’t have the same com-

plex challenges to keep you coming back.

The game begins with a full motion video scene
introducing you to the plot of the game and the video
scenes are intertwined throughout the missions. The
game play is very straightforward as you drive over
contraband, which is highlighted for your conve-
nience with yellow and red zones. Once you have
picked up the product(s), you must make a drop off at
a speciﬁc point. p

' These missions are very repetitive. The only real
difference between the missions are the vehicles that
range from a buggy to military tanks that can be
unlocked throughout the duration of the game as well
as the increasingly difﬁcult terrains to overcome in
Russia and Vietnam. V

When the police get on your tail in
the “Grand Theft” title, a good strategy is
needed to shake them because they will set
barricades and follow you with a helicopter.
But while dropping off contraband in
“Smuggler’s Run,” it is not all that difﬁcult to escape
the men in blue, because all they do is smash into you.

There really is no strategy in losing the police as
the key.to the game is racing back to the checkpoints.
This feature quickly becomes trite as the game lacks a
change of pace.

If you absolutely love racing games and time tri-
als then this might be the game for you, but if you’re
expecting another strong performance from the com-
pany that put out the wild “Grand Theft” title, you will
most likely be disappointed.

